Reverse Image Search¶

  • It is also known as Content-Based Image Retrieval (CBIR)
  • Program Flow:
    • Phase-1: Train the autoencoder
    • Phase-2: Extract features from all images in our dataset by computing their latent-space representations using the autoencoder
    • Phase-3: Compare latent-space vectors to find all relevant images in the dataset

Loading Dataset¶

  • Fashion-MNIST is a dataset of Zalando's article imagesconsisting of a training set of 60,000 examples and a test set of 10,000 examples.
  • Each example is a 28x28 grayscale image, associated with a label from 10 classes.
  • Label Description
    • 0 T-shirt/top
    • 1 Trouser
    • 2 Pullover
    • 3 Dress
    • 4 Coat
    • 5 Sandal
    • 6 Shirt
    • 7 Sneaker
    • 8 Bag
    • 9 Ankle boot

Building Convolution AutoEncoder¶

Defining Model¶

In [9]:
class ConvolutionAutoEncoder:
    '''Convolutional AutoEncoder Architecture'''
    
    @staticmethod
    def build(latent_dim, original_dim, filters=(32, 64)):
        '''
            Input: latent_dim => Bottleneck Dimension
                   original_dim => Input Dimension
                   filters => list of filters for Conv2D layer
            Output: It creates the architecture based on inputs
        '''
        
        # define the input to the encoder
        encoder_input = tf.keras.Input(shape=original_dim, name='InputLayer')
        x = encoder_input
        
        # loop over the number of filters
        for f in filters:
            # apply a CONV => MaxPool
            x = tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(filters=f, kernel_size=(3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same')(x)
            x = tf.keras.layers.MaxPool2D(pool_size=(2, 2), padding='same')(x)
        
        # flatten the network and then construct our latent vector
        volumeSize = x.shape
        x = tf.keras.layers.Flatten()(x)
        latent = tf.keras.layers.Dense(units=latent_dim)(x)
        
        # build the encoder model
        encoder = tf.keras.Model(encoder_input, latent, name='Encoder')
        
        ###########################################################################################
        
        # define the input to the decoder
        latent_input = tf.keras.Input(shape=latent_dim)
        x = tf.keras.layers.Dense(np.prod(volumeSize[1:]))(latent_input)
        x = tf.keras.layers.Reshape((volumeSize[1], volumeSize[2], volumeSize[3]))(x)
        
        # loop over the number of filters in reverse order
        for f in filters[::-1]:
            # apply a CONV_TRANSPOSE => RELU => BN operation
            x = tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(filters=f, kernel_size=(3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same')(x)
            x = tf.keras.layers.UpSampling2D(size=(2, 2))(x)
            
        
        # apply a single CONV_TRANSPOSE layer used to recover the original depth of the image
        output = tf.keras.layers.Conv2DTranspose(filters=original_dim[-1], kernel_size=(3, 3), activation='sigmoid', padding="same")(x)
        
        # build the decoder model
        decoder = tf.keras.Model(latent_input, output, name='Decoder')
        
        ###########################################################################################
        
        # our autoencoder is the encoder + decoder
        autoencoder = tf.keras.Model(encoder_input, decoder(encoder(encoder_input)), name="ConvolutionAutoEncoder")
        
        # return a 3-tuple of the encoder, decoder, and autoencoder
        return (encoder, decoder, autoencoder)

Analyzing Model¶

In [17]:
def plot_result(history, components=['loss', 'val_loss'], colors=['b','r'], labels=['Training loss', 'Validation loss'], locs=[5, -10]):
    '''
        Input: history => model training information
               component => element of data
               color => color to be used for plotting
               label => text for defining plots
        Output: plot of data component
    '''
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(20, 6))
    for component, color, label, loc in zip(components, colors, labels, locs):
        plt.plot(history.history[component], marker='o', color=color, label=label)
        plt.title('Loss')
        plt.legend()
        plt.xticks(history.epoch)
        for x, y in zip(history.epoch, history.history[component]):
            label = "{:.3f}".format(y)
            plt.annotate(label,                               # this is the text
                         (x, y),                              # this is the point to label
                         textcoords="offset points",          # how to position the text
                         xytext=(0, loc),                       # distance from text to points (x,y)
                         ha='center')                         # horizontal alignment can be left, right or center

Image Search¶

In [27]:
def display_search(images, searchResults):
    '''
        Input: images => list of images
               searchResults => list of search-results in format (index, distance)
        Output: montage display of images
    '''
    results = []

    # loop over the results
    for (d, j) in searchResults:
        # grab the result image, convert it back to the range
		# [0, 255], and then update the images list
        image = (images[j] * 255).astype("uint8")

        # as montages expects 3D image
        image = np.dstack([image] * 3)
    
        results.append(image)
  
	# build a montage from the results and display it
    dim = int(math.sqrt(len(searchResults)))
    montage = build_montages(image_list=results, image_shape=results[0].shape[:-1], montage_shape=(dim, dim))[0]

    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 7))
    plt.imshow(X=montage, cmap='gray')
    plt.title('Search Results')

Using Only Euclidean-Distance¶

  • Takes O(n) time to search
In [28]:
def euclidean(a, b):
	# compute and return the euclidean distance between two vectors
    return np.linalg.norm(a - b)
In [29]:
def perform_search(queryFeatures, searchData, maxResults=64):
    start = time.time()

    sr = math.sqrt(maxResults)
    assert ((sr - math.floor(sr)) == 0), "Choose maxResults a perfect square"

	# initialize our list of results
    results = []

    # loop over our index
    for i in range(searchData.shape[0]):
        # compute the euclidean distance between our query features
        # and the features for the current image in our index, then
        # update our results list with a 2-tuple consisting of the
        # computed distance and the index of the image
        d = euclidean(queryFeatures, searchData[i])
        results.append((d, i))

    # sort the results and grab the top ones
    results = sorted(results)[:maxResults]

    end = time.time()
    print('Time Took:', end-start)

    # return the list of results
    return results

Using Approximate Nearest Neighbors (Annoy) & Euclidean-Distance¶

  • Takes O(logn) time to search
In [33]:
# Create Annoy Index
def build_annoy_index(encoding_dim, encodings, num_trees=10, annoy_index_file='Annoy.annoy.index'):   
    ann = AnnoyIndex(f=encoding_dim, metric='euclidean')

    for index, encoding in enumerate(encodings):
        ann.add_item(i=index, vector=encoding.T)

    # builds a forest of num_trees, higher the number of trees, higher the precision
    ann.build(n_trees=num_trees)

    #save the index to a file
    ann.save(fn=annoy_index_file)
    print("Created Annoy Index Successfully")

In [35]:
def get_similar_images(querySearch, annoy_file_name, n_similar=64):
    start = time.time()

    sr = math.sqrt(n_similar)
    assert ((sr - math.floor(sr)) == 0), "Choose n_similar a perfect square"

    # Load the annoy index
    saved_ann = AnnoyIndex(f=querySearch.shape[-1], metric='euclidean')
    saved_ann.load(annoy_file_name)

    # get the nearest images 
    # get_nns_by_vector returns the most similar images

    end = time.time()
    print('Time Took:', end-start)

    return saved_ann.get_nns_by_vector(vector=querySearch.T, n=n_similar, search_k=-1, include_distances=True)
